\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri152\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin152\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp2057 {\fs24 
\par \tab A characteristic of the development of international organizations in the last half Century has been the shift in the locus of decision-making on a whole range of governance issues from national governments to int
ernational organizations. This process was not at first a major focus of attention, since organizations were initially cautious in the exercise of their limited powers and when organizations did make decisions that potentially bound Member States there wa
s a primary role given to State consent in the acceptance of such obligations. However this institutional landscape is evolving. International organizations have increasingly themselves interpreted their powers \endash  even of binding decision \endash 
 in an expansive manner that blurs the role of State consent,}{\cs16\fs24\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s15\qj \fi720\li0\ri230\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin230\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp2057 {
\cs16\fs18\super \chftn }{\fs18  For an account and analysis of the expansion, for example, by the European Community of its competences in a number of areas, see Weiler, J., }{\i\fs18 The Constitution of Europe}{\fs18  (1999), pp.44-56.}}}{\fs24 
 and States have increasingly conferred broader public powers of governance on international organizations.
\par \tab The broad range of measures being taken by international organizations in the exercise of conferred powers has provoked a considerable response from a variety of domestic
